  "method": "We propose Unsupervised Preference- and Anchor-guided Alignment (UPAA) for out-of-distribution vision–language alignment. UPAA keeps the original VLM largely frozen and inserts a lightweight visual adapter while upgrading the visual frontend for detail preservation. Concretely, we adopt an any‑resolution tiling frontend and a mixed-encoder fusion that concatenates features from a CLIP-like encoder and a DINOv2-style local-detail encoder, summarized by a Q‑Former into a fixed number of tokens. Inside a mid transformer layer we add a small set of learnable global attention maps as a domain adapter; only these maps, a shallow visual projection head, and prompt heads on the text side are trainable, preserving source-domain alignment while adding capacity to capture new spatial patterns.\n\nGiven only unlabeled target images, UPAA constructs self-supervised, clinically/semantically grounded pairwise preferences to preserve cross‑modal alignment. For each image, we generate K caption candidates using the base VLM (and optional open captioners) and compute saliency with self-supervised detectors (e.g., DINO/DINOv2 attention or SAM proposals). We form dispreferred pairs by (a) lesion/region neglect: occlude or locally perturb the top-salient region and pair the perturbed image with the original high‑scoring caption as a negative versus the unperturbed pair; and (b) plausible hallucinations: sample fluent alternative captions and select those whose CLIP score drops the least under salient‑region occlusion (i.e., text likely ungrounded) as dispreferred. We then optimize a pairwise preference loss that increases the similarity margin s(img, caption_pref) − s(img, caption_dispref) while keeping the text encoder mostly frozen. This makes the adapter sensitive to domain‑relevant regions without any ground‑truth labels.\n\nTo keep the joint space domain-invariant, we introduce text-anchored adversarial alignment. Build a bank of domain-agnostic anchors (colors, shapes, spatial relations) and optional domain lexicons mined from unlabeled corpora (e.g., radiology/satellite glossaries). A domain discriminator tries to tell whether an image–anchor pair embedding arises from source or target; we train the visual adapter through gradient reversal to confuse it, nudging target image embeddings toward the anchor-conditioned manifold already occupied by source pairs. If unlabeled in-domain text is available, we attach a lightweight MLM/adapter to the text encoder (initialized from a domain LM when possible) to better encode domain terms without supervision, stabilizing image–text scoring on jargon.\n\nFinally, UPAA prevents collapse and supports sub‑domain specialization via a multi-view prompting head. We maintain M prompt/view heads (e.g., generic, texture‑aware, geometry‑aware, domain‑term aware). For each target image, we select the head with the highest image–text score to pull closer, while gently pushing the remaining heads away (global–local loss). This encourages different heads to specialize to different target sub‑modes (e.g., retinal vs chest X‑rays; farmland vs urban satellite) without labels. Training alternates: (1) a few epochs of adversarial anchor alignment and any‑resolution adapter fitting; (2) preference optimization on the self‑constructed pairs; (3) short text‑side unsupervised updates if domain corpora exist. Inference uses tiling+fusion, evaluates all heads and a small prompt set, and reports the max score to remain robust under shift.",
  "rationale": "The core failure under unseen domain shift is that the visual features drift while the text space and alignment margins stay calibrated to web imagery. UPAA supplies three complementary, label-free signals that directly target this: (i) localized perturbation and hallucination-based preferences teach the model which image regions must support the text, preserving grounding where web pretraining is weakest; (ii) text-anchored adversarial confusion pulls target image embeddings toward known text manifolds without needing target annotations; and (iii) multi-view heads keep capacity diversified so that some pathways specialize to new appearance statistics instead of averaging them away. The any‑resolution, mixed-encoder frontend and small global-attention adapter provide the needed inductive bias and a low-parameter knob to absorb domain-specific spatial patterns while protecting source alignment.\n\nBecause all supervision comes from the model’s own captions, saliency maps, generic anchors, and optional unlabeled text, UPAA applies to medical and satellite images alike. It avoids brittle self-training on single pseudo captions by using preference pairs and worst‑case (saliency‑conditioned) negatives, which are more robust under shift. The result is maintained or improved image–text alignment on unseen domains without requiring any target-domain labels.",
