  "method": "We propose COMPASS, a test-time and continual, label-free adaptation layer that preserves vision–language alignment under unseen domain shift (e.g., medical, satellite) without target-domain labels. Starting from a frozen web-trained VLM (e.g., CLIP-like), we keep the text encoder fixed and adapt only a small set of vision-side modules: (i) a lightweight visual prompt front-end (pixel-level or early-feature prompts) and (ii) a factorized adapter that decomposes the visual representation into a shared, alignment-preserving pathway and a domain-specific modulation pathway. An exponential-moving-average (EMA) teacher of the full model anchors the original cross-modal geometry and prevents drift.\n\nThe domain-binding front-end couples two mechanisms. First, a learnable visual prompt bank is injected before or into the first few vision blocks, nudging inputs from the target domain toward the web pretraining manifold. Second, an amortized inference head estimates a per-image domain code z_dom that modulates intermediate features via a small FiLM/LoRA adapter stack, while a shared pathway passes gradients only through the adapters and prompts (the backbone remains frozen). We place a simple Gaussian prior over z_dom and regularize with a KL term so the domain-specific modulation remains compact and does not entangle with the shared alignment space. Both prompts and adapters are updated online, while the z_dom prior is refined slowly across the stream.\n\nUnsupervised alignment is maintained with three complementary signals. (1) Self-captioned contrastive alignment: for each target image, the VLM (or a small caption head) generates K candidate captions; we keep high-confidence text anchors and optimize an InfoNCE loss to increase image–text similarity for the top caption and decrease it for hard negatives (including other candidates and a fixed bank of generic web prompts). (2) Cross-view consistency: two strong augmentations of the same image must produce similar similarities over the caption bank, stabilizing the image embedding without labels. (3) Entropy shaping: we minimize entropy of the image–text similarity distribution over the candidate bank to produce confident, clustered alignments while avoiding collapse with temperature and teacher constraints.\n\nTo avoid catastrophic forgetting and preserve cross-modal geometry, we use a teacher–student consistency term: the student’s similarity matrix over a small replay buffer of web images and a fixed set of web text anchors is matched to the EMA teacher. We further add a lightweight domain discriminator on shared visual features with a gradient-reversal layer to keep the shared pathway domain-invariant; the domain-specific modulation absorbs style/content shift. Updates are uncertainty-weighted: per-sample confidence scores downweight noisy self-captions and limit prompt/adapter drift. Only prompts, adapters, z_dom inference, and the domain discriminator are trained; the text encoder, visual backbone, and the EMA teacher’s main weights remain frozen.\n\nDeployment: as target images stream in, we run a few inner-loop updates per batch with small learning rates and an uncertainty-guided EMA on the prompt bank. We cap compute by freezing deeper adapters, and apply early stopping when teacher–student discrepancy stops improving. At inference, the adapted prompts/adapters are used with the frozen text encoder; no target labels or paired texts are required, and the method remains open-vocabulary for downstream zero-shot queries.",
  "rationale": "Cross-modal degradation under domain shift stems from visual features drifting away from the text-aligned manifold. By freezing the text encoder and constraining adaptation to small visual prompts and domain-specific adapters, we retain the shared alignment while granting just enough capacity to absorb style/content shift. The domain-factorized design explicitly separates a stable, alignment-preserving pathway from a compact domain modulation controlled by a prior, reducing the chance that adaptation breaks the learned image–text geometry.\n\nBecause no labels are available, we rely on self-captioning and open-vocabulary text banks to create pseudo text anchors, but guard against error amplification with uncertainty-weighted updates, cross-view consistency, and teacher–student constraints on a web replay buffer. Adversarial alignment further nudges shared features toward domain invariance, while uncertainty-aware prompt updates keep compute low and adaptation stable. Together, these ingredients maintain cross-modal alignment in new domains without target supervision.",
